        "id": 1000008
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-20T18:51:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Your questions made me realize I really have 2 distinct inputs here:\n\n1) Something is wrong with the connection between the passive BMC and its host processor.  This is the one that would be detected by the hypervisor at/near runtime.  This may be remedied by a passive BMC concurrent maintenance operation at runtime and so the input could be cleared as part of that.\n\n2) Something is wrong with the passive BMC\u0027s host processor itself so that it can\u0027t be operational, like\n - it is deconfigured\n - it doesn\u0027t have any attached memory\n - the chassis it\u0027s in can\u0027t be powered on so the host processor can\u0027t run\n\nThis one is really the case that can be cleared on a power off, because there is no chassis CM, and the BMC won\u0027t know if any of these are fixed, so it will take a boot to find out.  If not fixed, that same code that called setRedundancyInput before would just call it again to disable redundancy.  It was pointed out that it wouldn\u0027t be possible for that code to give an \u0027all clear\u0027 doing the boot, which is why we have to clear it before the boot.\n\nI will separate these out.\n\nI guess I may as well add a boolean parameter to set it to true or false as well to make it more future proof.\n\nI know there won\u0027t be any external caller to clear case 2) on a boot, so I will still handle it myself on the power off.\n\nI\u0027m not sure yet about case 1) during the BMC CM, if someone will be able to call it to clear it or I would do it, but that can be dealt with when it comes up later.",
      "parentUuid": "a935f6bb_f36ec585",
